      "settings": {
        "heading": "About the book",
        "description": "<p>The Mughal Chronicles stands as the most comprehensive single-volume account of the Mughal Empire ever published in the English language. Now in its third revised and expanded edition, this landmark work by Professor R.C. Sharma has been the definitive reference for students, scholars, and enthusiasts of South Asian history for over two decades.</p>",
        "edition_heading": "About This Edition",
        "edition_text": "<p>The third edition incorporates findings from recently declassified archival material held at the National Archives of India, the British Library's Oriental Collections, and newly translated Persian primary sources from the Aligarh Muslim University. Over 80 pages of new content have been added, along with a comprehensive genealogical appendix.</p>",
        "inside_heading": "What's Inside",
        "inside_intro": "<p>Spanning from the founding of the empire by Babur in 1526 to its formal dissolution in 1857, the book is organized into six thematic parts:</p>",
        "inside_list": "<p>Part I — The Foundations: Babur, Humayun, and the Central Asian inheritance</p><p>Part II — The Consolidation: Akbar's administrative and cultural revolution</p><p>Part III — The Imperial Zenith: Jahangir and Shah Jahan — art, architecture, and power</p><p>Part IV — The Orthodoxy and Its Consequences: Aurangzeb and the politics of religion</p><p>Part V — The Long Decline: The later Mughals and the rise of regional powers</p><p>Part VI — The Twilight Empire: From 1803 to the Revolt of 1857</p>",
